  <h1>How Late-Pay Penalties Are Calculated</h1>
  <p>Late-payment math depends on context — B2B invoice versus employment final paycheck, contractual rate versus statutory default, flat fee versus accruing interest. This guide walks through each scenario with formulas and worked examples.</p>
  <p><em>Written by Emerson Park (EP), Contributing Writer — State Wage Codes, Paralegal (employment). Updated May 2026.</em></p>

  <h2>Scenario 1: B2B invoice or contract — contractual late fee</h2>
  <p>If your contract specifies a late fee and/or interest rate, that's the starting point. The standard formula combines a flat fee (if any) with daily-accruing interest:</p>
  <p><code>Total late charge = Flat fee + (Amount overdue &times; (Annual rate &divide; 365) &times; Days late)</code></p>
  <p>This is simple interest — calculated on the original principal, not compounded. The flat fee applies once, at the trigger point defined in the contract (e.g., "if invoice is more than 30 days past due"). Interest accrues daily from the due date until the invoice is paid.</p>

  <p><strong>Worked example 1 (flat fee + interest):</strong></p>
  <ul>
    <li>Invoice amount: $5,000</li>
    <li>Days overdue: 45</li>
    <li>Contract terms: $50 flat fee + 1.5%/month (18% APR) interest</li>
    <li>Interest = $5,000 &times; (0.18 &divide; 365) &times; 45 = $110.96</li>
    <li>Total late charge = $50 + $110.96 = <strong>$160.96</strong></li>
  </ul>

  <p><strong>Worked example 2 (interest only, no flat fee):</strong></p>
  <ul>
    <li>Invoice amount: $12,000</li>
    <li>Days overdue: 90</li>
    <li>Contract rate: 8% APR</li>
    <li>Interest = $12,000 &times; (0.08 &divide; 365) &times; 90 = $236.71</li>
    <li>Total late charge = <strong>$236.71</strong></li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Scenario 2: No contractual late terms — statutory interest</h2>
  <p>If your contract is silent on late fees, you can usually still claim statutory interest at your state's commercial rate when you pursue collection. This isn't a "fee" you can add to an invoice — it's recoverable in a collection lawsuit or negotiation, but it requires you to actually pursue payment formally.</p>
  <p>Common statutory commercial interest rates (these change; verify current rates with your state's statutes):</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>California:</strong> 10% per year (Cal. Civ. Code § 3289(b))</li>
    <li><strong>New York:</strong> 9% per year (CPLR § 5004)</li>
    <li><strong>Texas:</strong> 18% for written contracts, 6% for oral contracts (Tex. Fin. Code § 302.002)</li>
    <li><strong>Florida:</strong> Varies annually — set by Florida CFO based on Treasury bill rates</li>
    <li><strong>Illinois:</strong> 5% per year for money withheld without good cause (815 ILCS 205/2)</li>
    <li><strong>Most other states:</strong> 4–12% depending on the state and type of claim</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Having a contractual rate in writing is always better — it gives you a higher rate and lets you invoice for the late fee directly rather than waiting for a legal claim. If your contracts don't specify a late-fee rate, add one before your next engagement.</p>

  <h2>Scenario 3: Employment final paycheck — California waiting-time penalty</h2>
  <p>The most worker-favorable employment penalty in the country is California's waiting-time penalty under Labor Code § 203. It's separate from and in addition to recovering the unpaid wages themselves.</p>
  <p><code>Penalty = Daily wage &times; Days late</code> (capped at 30 days)</p>
  <p>Daily wage = (hourly rate &times; regular hours per day) OR (annual salary &divide; 260 working days)</p>

  <p><strong>Worked example — California (hourly worker):</strong></p>
  <ul>
    <li>Hourly rate: $25/hour, 8-hour day = $200/day</li>
    <li>Final paycheck 10 days late</li>
    <li>Penalty = $200 &times; 10 = <strong>$2,000</strong></li>
    <li>Plus recovery of all unpaid wages on top of the penalty</li>
  </ul>

  <p><strong>Worked example — California (cap applies):</strong></p>
  <ul>
    <li>Hourly rate: $35/hour, 8-hour day = $280/day</li>
    <li>Final paycheck 60 days late</li>
    <li>Penalty = $280 &times; 30 (capped) = <strong>$8,400</strong></li>
    <li>The extra 30 days beyond the cap produce no additional penalty — but you still recover the unpaid wages for all 60 days</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Scenario 4: Employment final paycheck — other state penalty structures</h2>
  <p>Other states use different formulas. The most significant:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Massachusetts (treble damages):</strong> Unpaid wages &times; 3, plus attorney's fees. No cap on the multiplier. $3,000 in unpaid wages = $9,000 in damages before attorney's fees.</li>
    <li><strong>Illinois (1% per day):</strong> 1% &times; unpaid wages &times; days late, plus attorney's fees. This is a percentage-of-amount structure, so it scales with the size of the unpaid balance. $5,000 unpaid &times; 1% &times; 20 days = $1,000 penalty.</li>
    <li><strong>Texas (treble damages, capped):</strong> The lesser of (unpaid wages &times; 3) or (4 weeks of wages), for willful violations. For workers with smaller unpaid balances, the 4-weeks cap rarely applies; for high earners, it can be binding.</li>
    <li><strong>Washington (double wages):</strong> Unpaid wages &times; 2, plus attorney's fees, for willful withholding of wages.</li>
    <li><strong>General rule in most states:</strong> Unpaid wages plus 25–100% statutory damages plus attorney's fees, often with a "willful" trigger for the multiplier. The exact percentage and what constitutes "willful" vary significantly by state.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>What's "reasonable" for a contractual late fee?</h2>
  <p>Courts apply the liquidated-damages doctrine: a late fee is enforceable if it's a reasonable pre-estimate of the harm caused by late payment. It's unenforceable if it's a "penalty" — disproportionately large compared to actual harm. The test is evaluated at the time the contract was formed, not at the time of enforcement.</p>
  <p>General benchmarks courts find reasonable:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>$25–$50 flat fees on invoices up to $5,000</li>
    <li>1–2% per month (12–24% APR) interest on commercial accounts — widely used and rarely challenged</li>
    <li>Higher rates (up to the state usury cap) for industries with high collection costs or short-term receivables</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Rates above 2.5% per month (30% APR) attract scrutiny in most states. Courts look at whether that rate bore a reasonable relationship to what the creditor would actually lose from delayed payment at the time the contract was written. A 5%/month rate on a routine service invoice would likely be struck down; a 5%/month rate on a 30-day short-term commercial loan might survive.</p>

  <h2>Compound vs. simple interest</h2>
  <p>Almost all late-fee calculations use simple interest. The formula is:</p>
  <p><code>Interest = Principal &times; (Annual rate &divide; 365) &times; Days</code></p>
  <p>Simple interest calculates only on the original principal. The interest doesn't itself earn interest — it just accrues linearly over time.</p>
  <p>Compound interest adds accrued interest to the principal at defined intervals (daily, monthly, annually) and then calculates future interest on the enlarged balance. For the same rate, compound interest produces a higher total — the difference is small over short periods but significant over years.</p>
  <p>Compound interest in late-fee clauses requires explicit contractual language — courts don't imply it. Even with explicit language, compound-interest provisions face additional scrutiny under state usury laws, because compounding can cause the effective annual rate to exceed the stated nominal rate. Our calculator always uses simple interest.</p>

  <h2>How to use the calculator</h2>
  <p>For B2B scenarios: enter the amount overdue, days past due, and your contractual annual interest rate. If your contract specifies a monthly rate (e.g., 1.5%/month), multiply by 12 to get the annual rate (18%). Add a flat fee if your contract specifies one. Select "B2B invoice / contract."</p>
  <p>For employment scenarios: enter daily wage in the "amount owed" field, days overdue, and select "Employment final paycheck." The calculator applies the California § 203 formula with the 30-day cap. For other states' formulas, use the numbers in this guide directly — the multipliers for Massachusetts and Texas don't fit the same input model.</p>
  <p>See <a href="/methodology">methodology</a> for the complete formula specification and edge cases. See <a href="/guides/final-paycheck-deadlines-by-state">final paycheck deadlines by state</a> for state-specific employment penalty rules.</p>
